      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex> be a category, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> be a fibred <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>-category ([SGA 1 VI 6.1]) with additive (resp. triangulated) fibres.
    We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:em>additive</fr:em> (resp. <fr:em>triangulated</fr:em>) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>-category (or that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is additive (resp. triangulated) over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>) if, for every arrow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>, the inverse image functor (determined up to unique isomorphism) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*\colon \mathcal {C}_Y\to \mathcal {C}_X]]></fr:tex> is additive (resp. exact).
    We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:em>abelian</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>-category if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is an additive <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>-category with abelian fibres, and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em>flat</fr:em> abelian <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {S}]]></fr:tex>-category if, further, the inverse image functors are exact.</fr:p>
